Url.Title: About DeployR Administration Console
Url.Abstract: The DeployR Administration Console, which is delivered with DeployR, is an easy-to-use web interface that facilitates the proper management and administration of your DeployR deployment. Accordingly, the following functions are supported in the console:

Url.Abstract: Who Can Access the Administration Console Only the admin user account, representing the administrator, has access to this console and can:

Url.Title: How to Access the Administration Console
Url.Abstract: How to Access the Administration Console Important! You cannot log in to DeployR from multiple accounts using a single brand of browser program. To use two or more accounts concurrently, you'll need to log in to each one in a separate brand of browser. For example, to log in to the DeployR Administration Console with admin account and into the API Explorer tool with another user account, you could open one in Google Chrome™ and the other in Mozilla® Firefox®.

Url.Title: Creating & Managing User Accounts
Url.Abstract: User accounts, which are created and managed in this Administration Console, provide authenticated access to the DeployR Web Services API, the API Explorer tool, and the Administration Console. Aside from the admin account, user accounts represent script authors, client application developers, or client application end-users.

Url.Title: Exporting User Accounts
Url.Abstract: Exporting User Accounts You can export user accounts into a CSV file. Exporting can be used to copy the accounts to another machine or to preserve them as a backup.

Url.Title: Importing User Accounts
Url.Abstract: Importing User Accounts Importing allows you to retrieve all of the accounts from a previously exported CSV file. Alternately, you can also import a CSV file you have created yourself using the proper format. Since role and boundary assignments cannot be exported, all imported user accounts are automatically assigned the BASIC_USER role at import time unless you choose to assign the POWER_USER role. You can, of course, manually add roles to users later after importing.

Url.Title: Managing Permissions with Roles
Url.Abstract: Users are granted permissions to perform operations on the DeployR Web services API by the role(s) assigned to them. Having clearly defined roles in this console simplifies the process of granting permissions to new or existing users.

Url.Title: Predefined System Roles
Url.Abstract: Predefined System Roles The following DeployR system roles are shipped with DeployR and can be assigned to user accounts.

Url.Title: Viewing, Editing, and Assigning Roles
Url.Abstract: Viewing, Editing, and Assigning Roles You can review, edit, and assign custom roles. System roles cannot be edited.

Url.Title: Creating Custom Roles
Url.Abstract: Creating Custom Roles While the system roles will suffice in many cases, there are times when it might be beneficial to create custom roles to constrain access to certain scripts according to a specific organizational, departmental, or functional need.

Url.Title: Deleting Custom Roles
Url.Abstract: Deleting Custom Roles While you cannot delete any of the system roles, you can delete a custom role. If you delete a custom role that is assigned to users, then that association between user and role is automatically removed upon deletion.

Url.Title: Exporting Roles
Url.Abstract: Exporting Roles You can export roles in a CSV file. Exporting can be useful when you want to copy the roles to another machine or to preserve them as a backup, for example. You can later import the contents of this file to this server or across multiple server deployments.

Url.Title: Importing Roles
Url.Abstract: Importing Roles Importing into the server database allows you to retrieve all of the roles from a previously exported CSV file. Alternately, you can also import a CSV file you have created yourself using the proper format.

Url.Title: Managing R Scripts
Url.Abstract: R scripts are repository-managed files containing blocks of R code with well-defined inputs and outputs. Each R script is designed to perform a specific function that can be exposed as an executable entity on the DeployR Web services API.

Url.Title: Exporting R Scripts
Url.Abstract: Exporting R Scripts You can export any scripts to which you have access into a CSV file. Exporting can be used to copy the scripts to another machine or across multiple deployments or to back up your scripts.

Url.Title: Importing R Scripts
Url.Abstract: Importing R Scripts Importing into the server database allows you to retrieve the scripts in a previously exported CSV file. Alternately, you can also import a CSV file you have created yourself using the proper format. If a script by the same name already exists, a new version of the script is created.

Url.Title: Managing R Boundaries
Url.Abstract: R boundaries are used to constrain runtime resource usage related to: R boundaries help manage the optimal allocation of resources across all operations. They also protect the system from poorly written or malicious code that may attempt to consume all system resources in an infinite loop or other threats.

Url.Abstract: Importing Boundaries You can import R boundaries from a CSV file into the server. This CSV file can come from a previous export or might be a file you created manually using the proper format.

Url.Title: Managing Access with IP Filters
Url.Abstract: Access to most DeployR services requires that the user be authenticated and have the proper permissions, which are determined by the system role(s) granted to that user. Access can be further restricted with an IP filter, which are managed in the IP Filters tab in this console.

Url.Title: Applying Filters
Url.Abstract: Applying Filters You can apply a filter to a specific node operating type in the Server Policies tab in this console so that all nodes designated for that type of operation inherit this IP filter automatically.

Url.Title: Exporting Filters
Url.Abstract: Exporting Filters You can export one or more IP filters into one CSV file. Exporting can be used to copy the IP filters to another machine or to preserve them as a backup. You can later import the contents of this file to this server or across multiple server deployments.

Url.Title: Importing Filters
Url.Abstract: Importing Filters You can import IP filters from a CSV file into the server. This file can come from a previous export or might be a file you created manually using the proper format.

Url.Title: Managing the Grid
Url.Abstract: Each node on the grid contributes its own processor, memory, and disk resources. These resources can be leveraged by the DeployR server to run R code as part of user authenticated, asynchronous, and anonymous operations.

Url.Title: Node Operation Types
Url.Abstract: Node Operation Types You must designate an operation type for each node on the grid. The following table describes the distinct types of operations recognized by the grid.

Url.Title: Grid Workload Distribution
Url.Abstract: Grid Workload Distribution There are two workload distribution models supported by the DeployR grid: Each node on the grid is assigned an operation type: authenticated, asynchronous, anonymous, or mixed mode. The operation type for a node indicates the types of operations that the node will accept at runtime. For example, a grid node configured for authenticated operations will only accept authenticated (project) operations at runtime and never accept asynchronous or anonymous operations. A grid node configured for 'mixed mode' accepts all types of operations.

Url.Title: Enabling or Disabling Nodes
Url.Abstract: Enabling or Disabling Nodes You can choose whether or not a configured node will be active in the grid or inactive using the Enable checkbox in the Grid Node Details page. When disabled, the node is no longer available to process any requests from DeployR and it will appear highlighted in the main grid node list.

Url.Title: Viewing or Stopping Slot Activity
Url.Abstract: Viewing or Stopping Slot Activity In the Grid Node Details page, you can review the slot activity. Additionally, you can shut down slots in order to terminate activity.This is a last resort for unwanted activity on the server.

Url.Title: Exporting Node Configurations
Url.Abstract: Exporting Node Configurations You can export one or more node configurations into one CSV file. Exporting can be used to copy the basic node configurations to another machine or to preserve them as a backup.

Url.Title: Importing Node Configurations
Url.Abstract: Importing Node Configurations You can import node configurations into the server from a CSV file you previously exported. You can import the contents of this file to same server from which it was exported or across multiple server deployments.

Url.Title: Monitoring Events
Url.Abstract: When you are logged in as admin, you can monitor the runtime grid and security events on the management event stream from the Home page. The management event stream allows you to see runtime grid activity events, grid warning events, and security access events. By default this stream is accessible to admin only; however, access can be changed in the Server Policies tab.
